<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0102</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Institution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> of Occupational Safety and Health – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Clause 1 – Health and safety at work: general duty of self-employed persons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IOSH strongly opposes exemption of certain self-employed from health and safety law as unnecessary, unhelpful and unwise and recommends retention of current legal coverage</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe there is no real burden on these duty holders from health and safety and so no benefit from exemption </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.86pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Exempting some self-employed brings risk of confusion, with others wrongly thinking they too are exempt </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Those in the exempt category may still pose possible risk to others (e.g. driving, varying activity, providing hair and beauty services or complementary therapies) </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are concerned exemption could encourage the growth of ‘bogus’ self-employment</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.41pt; padding-left:10.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As exemption only applies to non-employers, we believe it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is possible it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could discourage expansion and employment</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In Europe, an employer body representing small firms opposes such exemptions fearing creation of a two-tier market</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Clauses 50-57 – Legislation no longer of practical use:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IOSH fully supports ‘tidying of the statute book’ that maintains health and safety standards – but we believe the current system for this works and should be retained and strengthened if needed </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We are concerned more Ministerial powers for this could mean valuable protective laws are inadvertently lost, together with the independence and objectivity essential for public confidence</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.86pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK health and safety legislation has already been, and continues to be, extensively reviewed  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is already a well-established Law Commission system for removing redundant laws </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Clauses 58-61 – Exercise of regulatory functions: economic growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IOSH is strongly opposed to a ‘growth duty’ being imposed on the health and safety regulator and recommend </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that the Health and Safety Executive (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HSE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is exempted</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HSE’s main purpose is to prevent injury, illness, death and disaster and this will also help economic growth</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.86pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HSE takes a risk-based, proportionate approach and is positively regarded</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We believe good health and safety regulation and management is good for business</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HSE must take cognisance of the courts’ expectation that health and safety is put ahead of commercial interest</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.41pt; padding-left:10.14pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HSE’s Enforcement Management Model uses ‘economic advantage deliberately sought’ as a contributing factor for prosecution</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> to IOSH and our submission</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Founded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in 1945, the Institution of Occupational Safety and Health (IOSH) is the largest body for health and safety professionals in the world, with around 43,000 members in over 100 countries, including over 13,000 Chartered Safety and Health Practitioners. Incorporated by Royal Charter, IOSH is a registered charity, and an ILO international NGO. Our vision is: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">A world of work which is safe, healthy and sustainable</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our written evidence to the Joint Committee on the Draft Deregulation Bill</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> raises concerns about the health and safety implications of the following proposed clauses and makes recommendations:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Clause 1 – ‘Health and safety at work: general duty of self-employed persons’ [</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a deregulatory provision to exempt from health and safety law certain self-employed persons] </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Clauses 50-57 – ‘Legislation no longer of practical use’ [</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a general provision for the repeal or revocation of legislation which a Minister considers to be “no longer of practical use”]</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Clauses 58-61 – ‘Exercise of regulatory functions: economic growth’ [</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a duty on persons exercising certain regulatory functions to “have regard” to the desirability of “promoting economic growth”] </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:7.13pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As a general point, we would highlight a 2012 ‘business perceptions’ study, which suggests deregulatory programmes, such as the Government’s, can themselves contribute to perceived regulatory burden. We believe the programme should be reviewed, taking appropriate cognisance of these findings.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">2</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">IOSH positions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 1 – ‘Health and safety at work: general duty of self-employed persons’ </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IOSH is strongly opposed to exempting certain self-employed from health and safety law, which we believe is unnecessary, unhelpful and unwise. We call for the current legal requirements to be retained. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IOSH has publicly expressed serious concerns about this proposal since it was first mooted by the Government in 2010. We reiterated our position in a critique of the report ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Health and Safety: Reducing the burden</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">3, 4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and to both Lord Young of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Graffham</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and Professor </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Löfstedt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in connection with their reviews of health and safety legislation.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">5, 6, 7, 8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> And more recently, in October 2012, we highlighted our concerns during the HSE consultation into this subject.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">9, 10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Relevant extracts from our responses are presented here for the Committee’s convenience. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In our 2010 critique of the Policy Exchange report,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> IOSH said: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 40.2pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“We believe that taking sensible steps to protect yourself, others who you may engage to help you, and the public, is good for the self-employed person, good for their business and good for UK plc...people who are injured or are ill will need support from GPs, NHS and possibly social services. So, it makes economic sense all-round for people to take sensible steps to look after themselves at work.” </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We reiterated these points to Lord Young and in our 2011 evidence to Professor Löfstedt,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> IOSH said:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 40.2pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“The Davidson review into the implementation of EU legislation reports that a number of responses highlighted that there could be good reasons to over-implement EU legislation and that the extension of health and safety directives to include the self-employed was an example of this. The Federation of Small Businesses felt that such application was good discipline and the CBI that it would help achieve consistency.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Professor </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Löfstedt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> stated the following in his 2011 report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 40.2pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“The actual burden that the regulations currently place upon these self-employed may not be particularly significant due to existing exceptions in some regulations and the limited prospect of these being enforced but it will help reduce the perception that health and safety law is inappropriately applied.” </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This indicates that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he believes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the issues are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">about reality, but about misperceptions, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we recommend they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be addressed through education and awareness-raising. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The ‘consultation impact assessment’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> provided </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">no data on how much time or resources the self-employed spend on health and safety; but the evidence they did have suggested compliance is very low and that Local Authorities do not tend to proactively-enforce in lower risk situations, unless they receive a complaint. Self-employed people who employ fewer than 5 workers do not need written health and safety policies or risk assessments and if they do not employ anyone, do not have duties under the Health and Safety (Display Screen Equipment) Regulations. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the final impact assessment, consultation responses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(7 respondents) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and qualitative research </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(60 interviewees) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">were used to estimate time spent on health and safety by the self-employed.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The Draft Deregulation Bill Foreword cites a saving of £300,000 a year and, assuming the 800,000 self-employed to be exempted and overall saving figures are correct, we note that this would average a saving of only 37.5p each.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A European employer body (UEAPME) has opposed exemption from health and safety laws for small firms because of fear it would create a two-tier system in the internal market.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">11</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In this context, we would also raise the possibility that it could discourage some self-employed from employing people (because it only applies to non-employers) and encourage growth in ‘bogus’ self-employment. This issue was highlighted by Dame Rita </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Donaghy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in her 2009 ‘one death is too many’ review report.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">12</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition to being unnecessary and unhelpful, the IOSH 2012 response to the HSE consultation ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Proposals to exempt from health and safety law those self-employed whose work activities pose no potential risk of harm to others – CD242</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> highlights other flaws showing it is unwise:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 40.2pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“We believe the concept of reliably identifying those ‘who pose no potential risk’ to others to be flawed and unworkable and that the current requirements for the self-employed are not onerous and make good business sense. Exemption would give the wrong message and may encourage the unscrupulous to gamble with people’s safety and health.”  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The reason we believe the concept flawed is because potential risks will exist and if inadequately controlled, can result in harm. Also, the proposal could suggest a static situation; whereas, self-employed people may vary their activities, sometimes employing others and sometimes working in a ‘prescribed sector’ (high risk). In addition, many self-employed may drive on company business or provide goods / services to others.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In conclusion, IOSH is concerned that exempting certain self-employed from health and safety law could lead to lower health and safety standards for them and those affected by their activities; may cause confusion, with some wrongly believing others are also exempt; and may encourage the unscrupulous to take more risk, all leading to increased risk of injuries / illness. We note that the average fatal injury rate for the self-employed (2007-8 to 2011-12) was much higher (1.3 per 100,000) compared to that for employees for the same period (0.5 per 100,000).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">13</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:2.25pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clauses 50-57 – ‘Legislation no longer of practical use’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IOSH is opposed to this proposal to introduce a ‘new power to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">disapply</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> legislation no longer of practical use’, as applied to health and safety legislation. While we fully support keeping the statute book up-to-date and removing redundant legislation, providing standards are maintained, we believe there are adequate procedures for this. In addition to being unnecessary, we are concerned that Ministers could inadvertently seek the removal of health and safety legislation that was still of practical use.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Examples of the current system in action include the 1992-94 major review of health and safety law. This recommended substantial simplification and modernisation, including the removal of 7 pieces of primary legislation and 100 sets of regulations deemed no longer necessary.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">14 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">More recently, between 2006 and 2009, HSE operated a series of ‘simplification plans’, specifically aimed at reducing the administration requirements of health and safety legislation, including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consolidation of regulations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Since 2010, there have been two major reviews of health and safety law with the express aim of reducing so-called legislative ‘burdens’, by Lord Young and Professor </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Löfstedt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. There has also been a Government-run ‘Red Tape Challenge’ on health and safety law and a feasibility study by Richard Matthews QC into options for consolidating health and safety regulations.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In addition, there is currently a major review into the practical implementation of European Directives on occupational safety and health.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">16</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Importantly, the Law Commission (LC) has a ‘Statute Law Repeal’ team which examines legislation that is ‘no longer of practical utility’. It consults widely and Government Departments with an interest are invited to comment. LC typically reports on reviews roughly 5-yearly (1998, 2003, 2008 and 2012).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">17</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Repeal criteria are as follows:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 40.2pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“Candidates for repeal are selected on the basis that they are no longer of practical utility. Usually this is because they no longer have any legal effect on technical grounds - because they are spent, unnecessary or obsolete. But sometimes they are selected because, although they strictly speaking do continue to have legal effect, the purposes for which they were enacted either no longer exist or are nowadays being met by some other means.” </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To conclude, IOSH makes clear how important we think the independence and objectivity of the HSE is for public confidence in the system in our submission to the Triennial Review of HSE.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">18</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> We believe it is essential that health and safety regulation is free from (and seen to be free from) political bias. This is why we believe the current system of independent review by competent lawyers and adequate public and professional consultation concerning proposed legislative change are vital and must remain.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clauses 58-61 – ‘Exercise of regulatory functions: economic growth’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IOSH is opposed to a duty compelling the health and safety regulator ‘to have regard to the desirability of promoting economic growth’, which we believe is unnecessary and potentially damaging to the regulator’s primary duty of enforcing health and safety law, protecting life and limb and preventing disaster.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our April response to the ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Non-economic Regulators: Duty to Have Regard to Growth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consultation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">19</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> said:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 40.2pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“IOSH believes that the proposal to compel health and safety regulators to ‘have regard to growth’, fundamentally misunderstands that good workplace health and safety regulation already supports growth. It not only saves lives; it also supports business and sustains the economy.” </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Health and safety regulators take a proportionate and risk-based approach and there is an appeals process for duty holders with concerns about decisions. Effective regulation can help ensure good health and safety standards and working conditions, which in turn have been linked with higher productivity, profitability and customer and worker loyalty.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">IOSH is concerned that compelling the regulator to consider economic growth has the potential to divert their attention and cloud their judgement. Apart from the danger that health and safety will suffer and people will be needlessly killed, injured or made ill, the regulator could also lose authority and credibility. In addition, such regulators would not necessarily be qualified to judge the desirability of promoting economic growth anyway, as it is neither their speciality nor their responsibility. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is important to note that HSE’s Enforcement Management Model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">21</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> uses ‘economic advantage deliberately sought’ as a contributing factor for prosecution. In addition, HSE must also fulfil the expectation of the courts and case law. For example, in a 1998 case the court judged “If steps that they think should be taken to improve safety would have an adverse economic effect on the business enterprise in question – so be it.” [Harris </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> HSE and Evans]</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">22</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Finally, IOSH would like Government, Employer Bodies, Trade Associations and businesses to promote the business case and economic and social benefits of good health and safety management and regulation. Also, for the vital advisory and enforcement role of HSE to be adequately resourced. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">IOSH recommendations for Government</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Exempting certain self-employed; IOSH recommends Government:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ensures all the self-employed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> covered by health and safety law </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Addresses misconceptions through education and awareness-raising</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.86pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Reviews its deregulatory programme, taking cognisance of the ‘business perceptions’ study findings on the negative effects of large deregulatory exercises</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">2</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Provides full ‘impact assessments’ for all its proposals</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Provides clear guidance and access to good advice for self-employed people</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Non-economic regulators duty to ‘have regard’ to the desirability of promoting economic growth; IOSH recommends Government:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ensures this duty does </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> apply to health and safety regulators</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Recognises and publicises the enormous public and economic good that the country derives from effective health and safety regulation and provides adequate resources for its delivery </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.86pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ensures the new Fees for Intervention scheme is monitored and evaluated to check it works as intended and does not deter people from seeking regulator health and safety advice </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Promotes the free IOSH </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Li£e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Savings resources to help duty holders to better appreciate the economic and social benefits of good health and safety management and regulation</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Legislation no longer of practical use; IOSH recommends Government:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Ensures any new power does </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> apply to health and safety legislation</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.47pt; padding-left:7.08pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Acknowledges HSE’s performance in generally providing impact assessments that are deemed ‘fit for purpose’</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 34.86pt; padding-left:7.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Highlights the fact that health and safety law has already been repeatedly and extensively revie